The paper deals with the black-box complexity of optimization algorithms, which is a topic that falls under the category of theoretical computer science (cs.THE). However, the specific problem studied in the paper is related to optimization of Boolean functions, which is a topic that is often studied in the subfield of computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of XOR- and permutation-invariant functions suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of information theory (cs.IT). The fact that the algorithm used in the paper only uses 3-ary unbiased variation operators suggests that it may be relevant to the subfield of neural networks and evolutionary computation (cs.NE). Finally, the use of the LeadingOnes function class suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS).
